<font color="#FF0000">THE PROTECTED WILL NEVER KNOW</font><br>
<tt>Sun Jul  6 13:07:59 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
I have shared with my children that everything I learned about Life, love, War hate, anger, compassion; I learned in the rice paddie fields of South East Asia, fighting alongside a fellow AMERICAN.  That a lot about how you respond under fire, depends upon what family values you hold before you go to war.<br><br>
1. I learned that we are a great nation and that the people of the world view the U.S. as AMERICANS and not as politicians. That they crave the Freedom we so freely enjoy.<br><br>
2. That when you are away from home engaged in a war, you live for that moment. That for everyone back home, life goes on and for the most part they do not share the pains and sorrows of the American fighting men. That are also deprived of the rich trust, friendship and unity found in war. <br><br>
3. That, For those who have fought for it, Life has a flavor the protected will never know.<br><br>
4.  The American Fighting men should not be held responsible for the mistakes politicians make.<br><br>
5. That freedom and liberty is non-selective, and resides only in those who fight for it, and then cherish it. <br><br>
6. That it is not over, because buried in this society are the seeds of success for future generations, that being the children of all the servicemen who fought and died in Viet Nam and all other wars. These children have the traits of their fathers, passed on by us, and will certainly bloom and change our country. <br><br>
7. If it ever becomes necessary to protect our country in the ultimate battle, I feel confident that a group of Marines that I served with in Vietnam, although gray and older, will move to the front, reassure the unknowing, space ourselves properly and move out! <br>

